cie","Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","of Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Coventry, Warwickshire, England":"Coventry, Warwickshire, Anglie","Lower Peover, Cheshire, England":"Lower Peover, Cheshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1388–1416":"1388–1416","1390–1414":"1390–1414","1414–1477":"1414–1477","1365–1404":"1365–1404","1367–1409":"1367–1409","Abt 1409":"omkring 1409","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1367":"1367","1477":"1477","1388":"1388","1414 (19-29)":"1414","about 1413":"omkring 1413","1365":"1365","1409":"1409","about 1386":"omkring 1386","1416":"1416","Beeston, Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Somme, Hauts-de-France, Frankrig","Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Coventry, Warwickshire, England":"Coventry, Warwickshire, England","Lower Peover, Cheshire, England":"Lower Peover, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"1388–1416":"1388–1416","1390–1414":"1390–1414","1414–1477":"1414–1477","1365–1404":"1365–1404","1367–1409":"1367–1409","Abt 1409":"circa 1409","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1367":"1367","1477":"1477","1388":"1388","1414 (19-29)":"1414","about 1413":"circa 1413","1365":"1365","1409":"1409","about 1386":"circa 1386","1416":"1416","Beeston, Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Somme, Hauts-de-France, Frankrijk","Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Coventry, Warwickshire, England":"Coventry, Warwickshire, England","Lower Peover, Cheshire, England":"Lower Peover, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1388–1416":"1388–1416","1390–1414":"1390–1414","1414–1477":"1414–1477","1365–1404":"1365–1404","1367–1409":"1367–1409","Abt 1409":"about 1409","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1367":"1367","1477":"1477","1388":"1388","1414 (19-29)":"1414","about 1413":"about 1413","1365":"1365","1409":"1409","about 1386":"about 1386","1416":"1416","Beeston, Bunbury, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Somme, Hauts-de-France, France","Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","of Peover, Cheshire, England":"Peover Superior, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Beeston, Cheshire, England":"Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Coventry, Warwickshire, England":"Coventry, Warwickshire, England","Lower Peover, Cheshire, England":"Lower Peover, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beeston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","habitational name from any of the many places in England so called. Those in Nottinghamshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire were settlements where bent grass grew (Old English <i>bēos</i> ‘rough grass’ + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’). In Bedfordshire it probably denoted a settlement on a bend (Old English <i>byge</i> + genitive singular <i>-es</i> + <i>tūn</i>). The hamlet stands on a marked bend of the river Yvel. In Cheshire it is named from a rock, below which trading took place (Old English <i>byge</i> ‘commerce’ + Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone’). The reference is to a prominent crag where the remains of Beeston Castle stand. Compare   Beaston   and   Beeson  .","occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived in that part of a village known in Middle English as <i>bi este toun</i> ‘(place) at the east (end) of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   and   Beaston  ."]},{"name":"Beeson","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston  , a habitational name from a place called Beeston. The spelling reflects the local pronunciation of the Nottinghamshire placename, although this form is now quite widespread in England."]},{"name":"Beaston","meanings":["English: variant of   Beeston   (the more common form of the surname in England), a habitational name from any of various places called Beeston."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord William Beeston was born in 1388, in Beeston, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lord Thomas Beeston, was 23 and his mother, Margaret T Jesson, was 21. He married Clemence Mainwaring about 1413, in Lower Peover, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1416, in Peover Superior, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 28."},"et":{"1388–1416":"1388–1416","1390–1414":"1390–1414","1414–1477":"1414–1477","1365–1404":"1365–1404","1367–1409":"1367–1409","Abt 1409":"umbes 1409","1390":"1390","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1367":"1367","1477":"1477","1388":"1388","1414 (19-29)":"1414